<H2>Introduction</H2>
<P>Recently, I wrote <A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/aspnet/Frame_Work_Design.asp">an=20
article</A> on the development of a master-page framework in ASP.NET. =
Master=20
Page framework was an extension of the ASP.NET <CODE>UI.Page</CODE> =
framework,=20
and most of it is related to the static appearance of the Page. Then, I =
started=20
receiving emails about the dynamic behavior of pages, and controlling =
the=20
interactions between user-controls on a page, and communication between=20
different pages etc. So, I thought there is a need of discussion on this =
aspect=20
of the .NET Framework, and this would not be possible without mentioning =
the=20
Model-View-Controller Design Pattern, that is embedded everywhere in the =
ASP.NET=20
Framework. This article is composed of two parts. In the first part, we =
will=20
discuss in detail about the Model-View-Controller Design pattern in =
context to=20
ASP.NET, using UML, and finish our discussion with writing an example=20
application as a bonus for its implementation. In the next part of the =
article,=20
we=EF=BF=BDll wrap up our discussion with dynamic aspects of pages by =
explaining=20
different types of fine-grained controllers with their design and=20
implementation, and we=EF=BF=BDll discuss about the details of the HTTP =
pipeline too and=20
what is the best approach to use it; so stay tuned, lot to come :).</P>
<H3>Model-View-Controller Design Pattern:</H3>
<P>This is the classical and most famous of all design patterns =
especially when=20
we talk about User Interfaces. A user interface is basically a =
presentation=20
layer of some sort of model-data. If the data changes, the view is =
updated=20
accordingly, or vice-versa. In this particular scenario, if you look =
closely,=20
you can observe that there are two objects involved for performing this =
task,=20
i.e., a <B>View</B> and a <B>Model</B>. There might be more than one =
view of a=20
data model. Like, one view could be a Grid presentation, and other could =
be a=20
Graphical Plot of some sort, like Bar chart or Pie chart, or so. Here is =
how it=20
would look like:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age001_big.jpg"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image001.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge001.jpg"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"267"></A></P>
<P>I know, you should have these questions now, like how the view object =
would=20
talk with the model object and vice versa, and how we want to look at =
the model,=20
which part of the model will go to which view and which part of the view =
and=20
how. Now, we are talking about one other object, the controller object; =
this=20
controller object acts as glue between model and view. Controller object =
is=20
basically a business object, provides the answer how we want to view the =
data,=20
what rules should be applied for its presentation or so, and what will =
happen if=20
some one changes some parameters in the view, how to react to some =
key-board or=20
mouse events if this is an interactive application, and some times you =
need to=20
update the model and send messages to other views that the data is =
changed, so=20
that they can postback a request for updating their own contents. You =
will get=20
all these answers shortly!</P>
<H3>Robustness Analysis:</H3>
<P>This Model-View-Controller can be best described visually, using =
robustness=20
analysis, first introduced by Ivar Jacobson, in his award winning book =
on Object=20
Oriented Software Engineering (see reference below), and was further =
explained=20
by Doug Rosenberg et al in his book, Use Case Driven Object Modeling =
with UML.=20
Robustness Analysis involves analyzing the narrative text of use cases,=20
identifying a first-guess set of objects that will participate in those =
use=20
cases, and classifying these objects based on the roles they play, and =
it helps=20
you partition objects within a Model-View-Controller paradigm. =
Robustness=20
analysis enables the ongoing discovery of objects, and helps you ensure =
that=20
you've identified most of the major domain classes before starting any=20
additional design or development. Ivar has classified them as:</P>
<OL>
  <LI>=EF=BF=BDentity=EF=BF=BD objects depict long lived objects, deals =
mostly with the=20
  persisted states.=20
  <LI>=EF=BF=BDboundary=EF=BF=BD objects depict links between the system =
and environment,=20
  communicating.=20
  <LI>=EF=BF=BDcontrol=EF=BF=BD objects depict use-case-specific =
behavior. </LI></OL>
<P><B>Entity objects</B> are no more than the information or data your =
boundary=20
objects are looking for. These might be database tables, Excel files, or =
might=20
be "transient" session or cached data or so.</P>
<P><B>Boundary objects</B> are the objects with which the actors (for =
instance,=20
the users) will be communicating in your software system. These might be =
any=20
windows, screens, dialogs and menus, or other UIs in your system. You =
can easily=20
identify them while analyzing your use cases.</P>
<P><B>Control objects</B> (controllers) are the business objects or your =

business web-services. This is where you capture your business rules =
that are=20
used to filter out the data to be presented to the user he has requested =
for or=20
something. So, the controllers are actually controlling the businesses =
needs or=20
the business itself.</P>
<P>Here are the visual icons of these three UML stereotypes:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image003.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge003.jpg"=20
width=3D"534" height=3D"200"></P>
<H3>Rules of the game:</H3>
<P>Here are the four basic rules you should enforce when extracting =
these=20
objects while analyzing your use cases and making interaction diagrams =
among=20
these objects:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>Actors can only talk to the boundary objects.=20
  <LI>Boundary objects can only talk to controllers and actors.=20
  <LI>Entity objects can only talk to controllers.=20
  <LI>Controllers can talk to boundary objects and entity objects, and =
to other=20
  controllers, but not to actors. </LI></UL>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image005.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge005.jpg"=20
width=3D"537" height=3D"360"></P>
<P>If you look at the above figure, you can see the only access point =
for an=20
actor to reach any object is through the Boundary objects. Boundary =
objects=20
can=EF=BF=BDt talk with each other. While Control objects can talk =
freely with all of=20
the objects except that it has no access to the actor or the user of the =
system.=20
And the Entity objects can=EF=BF=BDt talk with each other too; they can =
access each=20
other but through the Control object. Also, an Entity object can only =
reach=20
Boundary object through the Control object. So the Control object is =
really a=20
media of communication between each layer, and that=EF=BF=BDs why it is =
suited for=20
business rules.</P>
<H3>Robustness Analysis and Model-View-Controller:</H3>
<P>Now, we have all the rules in place, let=EF=BF=BDs see how these =
objects are related=20
to Model-View-Controller paradigm. Well, good news is this, that they =
have=20
one-to-one mapping with the objects, derived from this analysis:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>Entity object maps to Model object,=20
  <LI>Boundary object maps to View object, and=20
  <LI>Controller is same in both. </LI></UL>
<P>And the other good news is that the same rules are applied to these =
objects=20
too. It means, when we are doing Robustness Analysis, we can use=20
Model-View-Controller objects in place of Entity-Boundary-Controller =
objects.=20
Here is how our objects would look like now:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image007.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge007.jpg"=20
width=3D"503" height=3D"200"></P>
<P>And here is the simplistic and hypothetical sequence diagram for MVC. =
What=20
you see in this diagram, a web-user initiated a query and an event is =
generated=20
that is handled by the controller and gets information that is needed =
from the=20
model, validates the information and passes back the result set to the =
view.</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image009.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge009.jpg"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"484"></P>
<P>Model-View-Controller is an approach for segregating different =
layers, in=20
such a manner that it can be easy to maintain for a moderate to very =
complex=20
application. It would be best suitable when you are making something for =
the=20
web, where the business rules change frequently with time. Also, =
it=EF=BF=BDs the best=20
way of writing applications in a service oriented architecture, where =
you=20
write/encapsulate your business rules in a separate web-service than the =

Data-Access Layer, where the service is only dealing with Model/Data =
related=20
stuff. Since the user interfaces are also separate, you can build =
powerful=20
Custom Controls, and put them in the User-Controls for deploying as =
Pagelets.=20
And finally, what is left, you need just to build proper interactions =
for them,=20
enforcing rules mentioned above, while designing any solution.</P>
<H3>Examples:</H3>
<P>So, let=EF=BF=BDs see where we stand now: we now know what these=20
model-view-controller objects are, how they look like, and what are the =
rules we=20
should enforce when we do analysis of a particular use case scenario and =
making=20
interaction diagrams out of them. Let=EF=BF=BDs take an example scenario =
and explain it=20
using this technique!</P>
<H4>Use case (UC.1.001):</H4>
<P><U>User shall be able to logon to the web-application.</U></P>
<P>Here is the UML diagram for this use case; it shows an actor =
(web-user) and=20
logon use-case relationship, it would more be elaborated when we go into =
the=20
analysis phase of it. I am taking a very simple case, of login and =
deferring the=20
registration use-case for our example, for making it simple and =
understandable=20
at the first go.</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image011.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge011.jpg"=20
width=3D"379" height=3D"216"></P>
<P>Before going into any analysis, it would be better, or I call it, =
it=EF=BF=BDs a=20
must, that you should have the visual prototype in front of you. Here is =
how our=20
prototype would look like:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image013.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge013.jpg"=20
width=3D"282" height=3D"150"></P>
<P>What it means, that the user is presented with a logon screen, where =
he can=20
enter his identity and press the Login button for access to the system. =
The user=20
can also turn on the check-mark on the check box for remembering him; in =
that=20
case, a cookie is needed on his system, to be enabled. Also, when he =
logs in, a=20
new session is created on the server side for keeping his activities =
alive while=20
using the web-application. With all these, let=EF=BF=BDs elaborate this =
scenario using=20
the Robustness Analysis diagrams:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age015_big.jpg"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image015.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge015.jpg"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"371"></A></P>
<P>Let=EF=BF=BDs take a closer look at the above diagram. User interacts =
with Logon=20
Screen (the view) that has one submit button for login (has-a =
relationship in=20
UML is shown with a diamond shaped line at one end), and has a checkbox =
for=20
enabling the cookie storage or so. What happens when the user clicks on =
any of=20
these two buttons, the request goes to the <CODE>MainController</CODE> =
object,=20
which then decides what to do with these actions, since it has all the =
logic=20
built for handling those events, and then does some validations from =
security=20
control object that in turn takes data from the Data Access object?=20
<CODE>MainController</CODE> then creates a session for this user, it =
also stores=20
user's info like encrypted passwords, in somewhere in the cookie store =
or so.=20
With this analysis, we are now very much clear that, apart from the =
logon=20
screen, there would be four other objects involved in this scenario;=20
<CODE>MainController</CODE>, <CODE>SessionState</CODE> object, the=20
<CODE>CookieStore</CODE> object and the Database Access objects. It does =
have=20
given you an idea what are the objects required to do a particular job, =
but it=20
does not tell you what functionality is needed for accomplishing this =
task. For=20
that, we need a sequence diagram, here is how the sequence diagram =
should look=20
like:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age017_big.jpg"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image017.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge017.jpg"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"468"></A></P>
<P>After careful study of the above sequence diagram, we can safely =
classify our=20
objects as there should be a <CODE>MainController</CODE>, that takes =
care the=20
business logic for the page, and a <CODE>BusinessService</CODE> object =
that=20
takes care of all the validation, Session Management and cookie setup =
stuff.=20
There would be a <CODE>DataAccessGateWay</CODE> (model) object that =
encapsulates=20
all the details of talking with the back end database. Here is how the =
class=20
diagram looks like:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age019_big.jpg"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image019.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge019.jpg"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"302"></A></P>
<P>Isn=EF=BF=BDt it beautiful that all of this robustness analysis leads =
us to a design=20
where we can define our first set of detailed class diagrams? I know =
you=EF=BF=BDll love=20
it.</P>
<P>The most important of all of the objects above, are the business =
objects that=20
are the controller objects. Now, let=EF=BF=BDs have a closer look at how =
ASP.NET=20
framework facilitates us in defining these Controller classes.</P>
<H3>ASP.NET and Model-View-Controller (MVC)</H3>
<P>Basic idea of MVC is to segregate the presentation layer from the =
business=20
layer and the Data Access Layer, or the model. Let=EF=BF=BDs see how it =
is done in=20
ASP.NET.</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image021.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge021.jpg"=20
width=3D"413" height=3D"263"></P>
<P>Let=EF=BF=BDs have a closer look at this picture, =
<CODE>Controller</CODE> is bound to=20
some model, and updates the <CODE>View</CODE> when the data changes or=20
vice-versa. So, the view depends on the model, passively. We achieve =
this goal,=20
with the code-behind feature of ASP.NET, the page/user-controls logic is =

separate from that of the view, that is presented either in =
=EF=BF=BD*.aspx=EF=BF=BD files or in=20
=EF=BF=BD*.ascx=EF=BF=BD files. And the controls you add to the =
page-controller, i.e.=20
<CODE>System.UI.Page</CODE>, you try to make them data-bounded as much =
as=20
possible for consistency and synchronization. And also, you embed your =
event=20
handler=EF=BF=BDs logic in the page controller using the code-behind =
feature. And if=20
your architecture is service-oriented architecture, then you can =
introduce=20
another controller as a business service (might be security service) =
that talks=20
to the back-end model as needed and returns secured data to the Page =
Controller.=20
Here is how it would look like:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image023.jpg" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge023.jpg"=20
width=3D"597" height=3D"600"></P>
<H3>It's Showtime (bonus++):</H3>
<P>As a bonus, we would be developing a full fledged master-details web=20
application that will give you enough details about =
model-view-controller (MVC)=20
and its inner working, as well as a way of communication between =
different=20
user-controls without even knowing each other. Also, with it =
you=EF=BF=BDll get a=20
reusable library that is composed of classes =
<CODE>OleDataLinkAdapter</CODE> and=20
<CODE>MsSqlDataLinkAdapter</CODE>. These objects are wrappers around =
ADO.NET=20
Connection and Command objects.</P>
<H4>Master-Details ASP.NET Application</H4>
<P>The application is a web-application that has a master-page composed =
of a=20
company logo, a banner, main contents, and footer. Main contents should =
display=20
a parent-child relationship in the form of grid-view. There shall be two =
grids,=20
the top one would be the master grid and the bottom would be the details =
one.=20
When the user clicks on any item in the master view, the details/child =
view=20
changes accordingly and should display the related child data.</P>
<P>Use-Case001: User shall be able to view/manipulate the master-details =
for=20
Northwind Customer/Orders tables.</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image025.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge025.png"=20
width=3D"351" height=3D"240"></P>
<P>We would be applying the same technique as in my previous article, =
that is=20
Pattern Oriented Architecture and Design (POAD). For this, we need the=20
prototypic pattern of our system we are planning to design. And here is =
how the=20
prototype would look like:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age027_big.png"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image027.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge027.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"431"></A></P>
<P>So, what we see is what we get, that is, our application would be =
composed of=20
a <CODE>MasterPage</CODE>, an HTML frame container, then HTML Table, and =
this=20
table would contain further the two controls, Master-User-Control and =
the=20
Details-User-Control. These user controls in turn would contain the=20
<CODE>MasterDataGrid</CODE> and <CODE>DetailsDataGrid</CODE> Views. Here =
is the=20
static inventory of the objects, needed to fulfill this job:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image029.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge029.png"=20
width=3D"549" height=3D"288"></P>
<H4>Robustness Analysis of the Use-Case001</H4>
<P>We now have some understandings of the objects needed to fulfill this =
job,=20
but before going into the detailed design, we need to analyze the use =
cases, to=20
find-out the proper interactions and relationships among them. This =
would be=20
done using the Robustness Analysis, while keeping into our mind the MVC =
concept.=20
Let's draw the conceptual Robustness Diagram for this scenario:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age031_big.png"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image031.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge031.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"332"></A></P>
<P>What it means, that the user is presented with a master-details view. =
The=20
upper Master-Grid-view is used to select the master table items. So, =
whenever=20
the user selects master item, the child view is updated accordingly. =
Let's see=20
how we achieve these interactions between objects. Look at the above =
diagram=20
closely and you will see that when the user selects an item from the=20
master-grid-view, the <CODE>MasterUserControl</CODE> would be notified, =
and that=20
in turn notifies this event to the listener, that is the=20
<CODE>MainController</CODE> object. <CODE>MainController</CODE> object =
would=20
notify about this event to the other listener, the=20
<CODE>DetailsUserControl</CODE>.</P>
<P>These user-controls have direct access to the Model=20
(<CODE>DataAccessGateway</CODE>) that uses =
<CODE>MsSqlDataLinkAdapter</CODE> to=20
establish MS-SQL database connections (for OLEDB connections, use the =
other=20
adapter, <CODE>OleDataLinkAdapter</CODE>). This is a classic example of =
the MVC=20
and its inner working. Here is the object interaction diagram for this=20
particular scenario:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image033.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge033.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"432"></P>
<P>The <CODE>MasterController</CODE> and the =
<CODE>DetailsController</CODE> are=20
differential Controllers, that they are responsible of controlling one=20
User-Control at a time and fine tune them while the =
<CODE>MainController</CODE>=20
object acts as an integrator, or a channel for these two controllers to =
pass=20
information to and fro between them. Let's see how we are planned for =
them to=20
work. For an object being a Notifying object, needs to implement the=20
<CODE>INotifier</CODE> interface, while a Listener object needs to =
implement the=20
<CODE>IListner</CODE> interface. Also, a listener object needs to attach =
itself=20
with the relevant notifier in-order for being notified. In our case, we =
have the=20
Master-Controller and, the Details-Controller is the listener.=20
<CODE>MainController</CODE> is both listener and notifier, and acts as =
glue=20
between them.</P>
<P>Now, at this point, we have all the information about the objects,=20
responsible for doing the job, how they would look like, and about their =

behavior and functionality. Let's now design them and develop the =
complete class=20
design. And here is the detailed class diagram for this application:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age035_big.png"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image035.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge035.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"455"></A></P>
<H2>Implementation using C# and ASP.NET</H2>
<P>Code hierarchy is shown in the following figure, where you will find=20
DataAccess adapters in <I>Shams.Data.dll</I>, updated MasterPage =
Framework=20
library in <I>Shams.Web.UI.MasterPages.dll</I>, and I have collected =
some=20
libraries from different sources on the web, you=EF=BF=BDll find them =
under=20
<I>Shams.Web.UI.WebControls.dll</I>. The sample application is in=20
<CODE>Shams.MVC.WebApp</CODE> namespace. All you need is to open=20
<I>Shams.MVC.WebApp</I> solution and you are ready to go. And verify the =
virtual=20
path in the file =
=EF=BF=BD<I>Shams.MVC.WebApp.csproj.webinfo</I>=EF=BF=BD to be created =
in the=20
IIS. Here is the one for it:</P><PRE =
lang=3D"text">&lt;VisualStudioUNCWeb&gt;=0A=
=0A=
&lt;Web URLPath =3D =
"http://localhost/shams/MVC/WebApp/Shams.MVC.WebApp.csproj" /&gt;=0A=
=0A=
&lt;/VisualStudioUNCWeb&gt;</PRE>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image037.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge037.png"=20
width=3D"530" height=3D"595"></P>
<P>Here are some code snippets, from the application, starting with the=20
<I>web.config</I>. The <CODE>AppSettings</CODE> section in the =
<I>web.config</I>=20
file would contain two things for this application, the connection =
string for=20
the NorthWind <CODE>DataTable</CODE>, and the path to the=20
<CODE>MasterPageUserControl</CODE>.</P>
<P>Here is how it does look like:</P><PRE lang=3D"xml"><SPAN =
class=3D"code-keyword">&lt;</SPAN><SPAN =
class=3D"code-leadattribute">appSettings</SPAN><SPAN =
class=3D"code-keyword">&gt;</SPAN>=0A=
  <SPAN class=3D"code-keyword">&lt;</SPAN><SPAN =
class=3D"code-leadattribute">add</SPAN> <SPAN =
class=3D"code-attribute">key</SPAN><SPAN =
class=3D"code-keyword">=3D"</SPAN><SPAN =
