class=3D"code-keyword">&gt;</SPAN></PRE>
<P>The model is the <CODE>DataAccessGateway</CODE> class and it returns =
the=20
<CODE>DataSet</CODE> that=EF=BF=BDs been used in the Master-Details data =
grid controls.=20
Here is how it looks like:</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D"image039.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge039.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"597"></P>
<P>It uses the <CODE>MsSqlDataLinkAdapter</CODE> that is a wrapper =
around=20
<B>ADO.NET</B> connection and command objects. This is a singleton =
class, with=20
all of its functions being static. Here is the skeleton of this =
class:</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age041_big.png"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image041.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge041.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"500"></A></P>
<P>In our particular scenario, <CODE>DataAccessGateway</CODE> uses this =
class,=20
to connect to the MS-SQL NorthWind database, by calling the=20
<CODE>Connect(.)</CODE> function of it. Once you have this connection =
object,=20
you call another function <CODE>FilldataSet(.)</CODE> to return you a =
brand-new=20
dataset being used for data-binding. Once it is done, you call=20
<CODE>Disconnect(.)</CODE> to close the connection object.</P>
<P>Other notable classes are the controller classes,=20
<CODE>UcMasterDetails</CODE> (Main-Controller) and two other classes,=20
<CODE>UcMainContentsMaster</CODE> (Master Controller) and=20
<CODE>UcMainContentsDetails</CODE> (Details Controller). Here is how we=20
connected these two classes with each other using =
<CODE>UcMasterDetails</CODE>=20
as a mediator.</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age043_big.png"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image043.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge043.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"443"></A></P>
<P>And finally! Here is how the application would look like when you run =
it.=20
:)</P>
<P><A =
href=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/im=
age045_big.png"=20
target=3D"_blank"><IMG alt=3D"image045.png" =
src=3D"http://www.codeproject.com/KB/architecture/ModelViewController/ima=
ge045.png"=20
width=3D"600" height=3D"347"></A></P>
<P>The MVC pattern I used in the application is the minimal use of it, =
but it=EF=BF=BDs=20
the best pattern being used in all the navigations between pages and =
between=20
controls. It also depends on how you plot a plan for your application in =
making=20
a prototype application. So folks, that=EF=BF=BDs it for now, I have =
tried to un-cover=20
everything about the MVC design pattern, with some useful applications =
for its=20
implementation. This is one of the most commonly used and misunderstood =
pattern.=20
I tried to make it simple and give you all the details it carries, along =
with=20
the robustness analysis, that=EF=BF=BDs the key in analyzing such =
applications.</P>
<H4>Improvement:</H4>
<P>There is always a point of improvement in any system, and the same =
here is=20
applicable too. I haven=EF=BF=BDt talked about any efficiency related =
stuff, because=20
that itself needs a full article. So, I am putting this responsibility =
on you to=20
go through the documentation for improving efficiency of ASP.NET =
applications,=20
like Caching, View-State Management and Session Management, and How to =
avoid=20
round-trips to the server, like post-backs etc. And I would appreciate =
if you=20
involve me in your findings, thank you very much.</P>
<H2>Question-Answers Session:</H2>
<LI>Q) What do you consider when architecting and implementing a new =
system=20
being successful?=20
<LI>A) Your vision should be broad when you architect or design it, and =
should=20
be focused while implementing it.=20
