                            <TD colSpan=3D"2">Well, for some people both =
terms=20
                              could be used to describe =
MVC:<BR>&nbsp;<BR>"A=20
                              design pattern is a formal way of =
documenting=20
                              successful solutions to problems. The idea =
was=20
                              introduced by the architect Christopher =
Alexander=20
                              and has been adapted for various other=20
                              disciplines"<BR>&nbsp;<BR>"A software =
framework is=20
                              a re-usable <B>design </B>for a software =
system=20
                              (or subsystem). A software framework =
<B>may</B>=20
                              include support programs, code libraries, =
a=20
                              scripting language, or other software to =
help=20
                              develop and glue together the different =
components=20
                              of a software project. Various parts of =
the=20
                              framework may be exposed through an =
API."<BR>-from=20
                              wikipedia citation of: Johnson, R. E. and =
B. Foote=20
                              (1988). =E2=80=9CDesigning reusable =
classes.=E2=80=9D Journal of=20
                              object-oriented programming 1(2): =
22-35.<BR>
                              &nbsp;<BR>Those definitions apparently =
suggest the=20
                              difference between a design pattern and a=20
                              framework are only the "support programs, =
code=20
                              libraries, a scripting language, or other =
software=20
                              to help develop and glue together the =
different=20
                              components of a software =
project".<BR>&nbsp;<BR>
                              So, MVC could be defined as a Design =
pattern AND=20
                              as a Framework, the latter not being an =
accurate=20
                              definition since it doesn't provide any =
base=20
                              code/libraries.<BR>&nbsp;<BR>Guarita - =
